                     <interp inst="def1-1648-18430508" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1648-18430508" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES JOHNSON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430508-1648-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430508-1648-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430508-1648-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18430508-cd-229" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430508-1648-offence-1 t18430508-cd-229"></join>7th of May</rs>, 1 purse, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 half-sovereign, and 2 shillings, the property of <persName id="t18430508-name-1273" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1273" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1273" type="surname" value="NOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1273" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430508-1648-offence-1 t18430508-name-1273"></join>Stephen Nott</persName>; from the person of <persName id="t18430508-name-1274" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1274" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1274" type="surname" value="NOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1274" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430508-1648-offence-1 t18430508-name-1274"></join>Martha Nott</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430508-name-1275" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1275" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1275" type="surname" value="NOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1275" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>MARTHA NOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Stephen Nott—he lives at an hotel in Oxford-street—on the 7th of May, I and my husband were going in a steam<lb></lb>boat from Hungerford pier to the Tunnel pier—there was a great rushing behind me—I felt a pull at my bag in which I had a purse and in it a half-sovereign—I turned and saw the prisoner take his hand out of my bag—he was close to me—I said, "What business have you to put your hand in my bag?"—he said, "I beg your pardon, you must be mistaken"—I said, "My purse is in your hand"—my purse was in his hand—I took him by the collar and called to my husband, and said, "This man has taken my purse"</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184305080166"></xptr>
               <p>—I saw him put his hand down by his side, and under his coat—he was accompanied by a female and another man—the female was as close as possible to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILKINS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Most of the people were crowding to get on shore? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—my husband was just before me—I had my hand just through his arm—I did not say "Some of these people have taken my purse"—I never searched my bag till I got to the office.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did not your husband request you to look into your bag, and did you not say to him "If anything is gone, I know that must be the man?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not, nor anything of the kind—my husband was a little before me, when I said the prisoner had my purse, and when he begged my pardon, and said I must be mistaken—he could not have the same opportunity of seeing the prisoner that I had, as I was pushed behind him by the other persons—I was not rushing—the prisoner was close at my left hand, when he put his hand into my bag—this is the bag—I was carrying it on my wrist—I felt the string cut my wrist—I had a pocket handkerchief and a letter in my bag, and the money was in my purse—the prisoner offered no resistance—he behaved with the greatest politeness—he did not say that he was going to Greenwich, but to oblige me, and to convince me, he would go on shore—he said in the office that he was going to Greenwich.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Court. Q.</hi> Are you sure he had his hand in your bag? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430508-name-1276" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1276" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1276" type="surname" value="NOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-1276" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>STEPHEN NOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. As I was coming out of the steam-packet, my wife called to me for assistance, saying, this man had robbed her—I took him by the arm and gave him into custody to the first officer I found—he was very willing to go at first, but at last he wanted to know whether I intended to take him or not—I said, "Yes."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q</hi> Did he not say, "Surely you can't be in earnest, in intending to take me?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He did—the people were pressing on me on all sides.</p>
               <p>
